<section xml:id="sec-adding-and-subtracting-rational-expressions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Adding and Subtracting Rational Expressions</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Adding rational expressions is similar to adding (numerical) fractions. Recall that to add fractions, you need to have the denominators be equal, and then you add the numerators.
    </p>
    
    <example>
      <title>Adding Two Fractions</title>
      <p>
        For example, to add <m>\frac{3}{5} + \frac{1}{5}</m>, we simply add the numerators, because the denominators are the same,
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{3}{5} + \frac{1}{5} = \frac{4}{5}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      In general, if the denominators are the same (that is, we have a common denominator), then simply add the numerators together over that common denominator. That is,
      <md>
        <mrow>\frac{a}{c} + \frac{b}{c} = \frac{a + b}{c}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    
    <p>
      If the denominators are not equal, then we need to first manipulate the fractions so that they have a common denominator.
    </p>
    
    <example>
      <title>Adding Two Fractions with Different Denominators</title>
      <p>
        For example, to add <m>\frac{4}{9} + \frac{1}{3}</m>, we have denominators of 9 and 3, so we can make a common denominator of 9, by multiplying <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> by <m>\frac{3}{3}</m>,
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{4}{9} + \frac{1}{3} \amp = \frac{4}{9} + \frac{1}{3} \cdot \frac{3}{3} \amp\amp \text{making a common denominator}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{4}{9} + \frac{3}{9}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{7}{9} \amp\amp \text{adding numerators}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      Sometimes, to make a common denominator, you need to manipulate both fractions.
    </p>
    
    <example>
      <title>Adding Two Fractions with Different Denominators</title>
      <p>
        For example, to add <m>\frac{3}{5} + \frac{2}{7}</m>, we have denominators of 5 and 7, so we need a common denominator of <m>35</m> (which is <m>5 \times 7</m>),
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{3}{5} + \frac{2}{7} \amp = \frac{3}{5} \cdot \frac{7}{7} + \frac{2}{7} \cdot \frac{5}{5} \amp\amp \text{making a common denominator}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{21}{35} + \frac{10}{35}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{31}{35} \amp\amp \text{adding numerators}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <example>
      <statement><m>\text{Add } \frac{1}{3}+\frac{5}{4}</m></statement>
      <answer><m>\frac{19}{12}</m></answer>
    </example>
    
    <example>
      <statement><m>\text{Subtract } \frac{5}{9}-\frac{2}{3}</m></statement>
      <answer><m>-\frac{1}{9}</m></answer>
    </example>
  </introduction>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-adding-rational-expressions">
    <title>Adding Rational Expressions</title>
    
    <example>
      <title>Adding Rational Expressions with Like Denominators</title>
      <p>
        To add <m>\frac{4}{x+2} + \frac{3}{x+2}</m>, add the numerators over the common denominator of <m>x+2</m>,
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{4}{x + 2} + \frac{3}{x + 2} = \frac{4 + 3}{x + 2} = \frac{7}{x + 2}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <example>
      <title>Adding Rational Expressions with Like Denominators</title>
      <p>
        To add <m>\frac{2x - 1}{x + 3} + \frac{1 - x}{x + 3}</m>, add the numerators together over the common denominator of <m>x+3</m>,
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{2x - 1}{x + 3} + \frac{1 - x}{x + 3} \amp = \frac{2x - 1 + 1 - x}{x + 3}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{x}{x + 3}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      To add two rational expressions with like denominators, add their numerators and keep the same denominator. That is, if <m>A, B, C</m> are polynomials, then,
      <md>
        <mrow>\boxed{\frac{A}{C} + \frac{B}{C} = \frac{A + B}{C}}</mrow>
      </md>
      with the restriction that <m>C</m> cannot be equal to 0.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Sometimes, after adding, the result can be further simplified by cancelling common factors.
    </p>
    
    <example>
      <title>Adding Rational Expressions and Simplifying</title>
      <p>
        For example,
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{4x}{15} + \frac{8x}{15} \amp = \frac{4x + 8x}{15} \amp\amp \text{adding}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{12x}{15} \amp\amp \text{collecting like terms}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{4x}{5} \amp\amp \text{cancelling common factor of 3}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-summary-rational-expressions">
    <title>Summary of Adding or Subtracting Rational Expressions</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Factor the denominators completely.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Create a common denominator, by manipulating each fraction.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          After you have a common denominator, add or subtract the numerators, and keep that common denominator.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Simplify if needed, by collecting like terms, and factor and cancel if possible.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Note: <m>\frac{A}{B+C} \neq \frac{A}{B} + \frac{A}{C}</m>. For example, <m>\frac{2}{3} \neq \frac{2}{2} + \frac{2}{1} = 3</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  
